title: Cerveza-Battered Fish Tacos with Quick-Pickled Onion and Cucumber
summary: Need a dairy free and pescatarian main course? Cerveza-Battered Fish Tacos with Quick-Pickled Onion and Cucumber could be an outstanding recipe to try. This recipe serves 4. One serving contains 952 calories, 51g of protein, and 13g of fat. For $5.16 per serving, this recipe covers 40% of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. A couple people made this recipe, and 48 would say it hit the spot. This recipe is typical of Mexican cuisine. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes roughly 30 minutes. It is brought to you by Foodnetwork. A mixture of apple cider vinegar, beer, salt, and a handful of other ingredients are all it takes to make this recipe so delicious. To use up the salt you could follow this main course with the Apple Turnovers Recipe as a dessert. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 94%. This score is excellent. Similar recipes are Cerveza-Battered Fish Tacos with Quick-Pickled Onion and Cucumber, Quick Cucumber And Red-onion Pickled Salad, and Beer Battered Fish Tacos.

winePairing.pairingText: Pinot Grigio, Gruener Veltliner, and Pinot Noir are my top picks for Fish. Fish is as diverse as wine, so it's hard to pick wines that go with every fish. A crisp white wine, such as a pinot grigio or Grüner Veltliner, will suit any delicately flavored white fish. Meaty, strongly flavored fish such as salmon and tuna can even handle a light red wine, such as a pinot noir. One wine you could try is La Fiera Pinot Grigio. It has 4 out of 5 stars and a bottle costs about 7 dollars.

productMatches.title: La Fiera Pinot Grigio
productMatches.description: This wine has a light straw color with green tints. It has a light floral and fruity bouquet featuring apples and pears. The palate is bright, fresh and dry showing nice balance and a lingering acidity perfect for a variety of lighter cuisine.Blend: 100% Pinot Grigio

instructions: Fill a large pot with oil halfway up the pot. Heat oil to 350 degrees F. Preheat grill.                          In a medium bowl, mix together 1 cup flour, cumin, cayenne, and salt. Slowly whisk in beer until thick, but not runny. Dredge fish in remaining flour first, then dunk in the batter. Fry in batches until golden brown, about 5 minutes. Drain on paper-toweled lined plate.                          Meanwhile, grill tortillas on grill.                          Serve fish in tortillas topped with Quick-Pickled Onion and Cucumber.                          In a medium saucepan, bring to a boil the vinegar, sugar, water, and salt. Add onions and cucumber and continue to cook a few minutes more. Remove from heat, add chile, and transfer to a bowl. Let cool slightly then chill covered, for at least 1 hour.                          Toss in the tomato and cilantro, 5 minutes before serving.

steps.step: Fill a large pot with oil halfway up the pot.
Heat oil to 350 degrees F. Preheat grill.

In a medium bowl, mix together 1 cup flour, cumin, cayenne, and salt. Slowly whisk in beer until thick, but not runny. Dredge fish in remaining flour first, then dunk in the batter. Fry in batches until golden brown, about 5 minutes.
Serve fish in tortillas topped with Quick-Pickled Onion and Cucumber.
In a medium saucepan, bring to a boil the vinegar, sugar, water, and salt.
Add onions and cucumber and continue to cook a few minutes more.
Remove from heat, add chile, and transfer to a bowl.
Let cool slightly then chill covered, for at least 1 hour.
Toss in the tomato and cilantro, 5 minutes before serving.
